text.tspan: 10) All attempts shall be made by Superintendent and General Manager to negotiate with the yard to minimise the total time taken forrepairs and dry-docking6.5.2AT THE DRY DOCK, REPAIR YARD OR BERTH1) Throughout the period of the docking / repair the Superintendent shall be in attendance and shall be in complete charge for thesupervision and verification of the jobs undertaken. No jobs shall be undertaken by the yard or ship staff without the approval of theSuperintendent.2) Superintendent shall work out the daily meeting schedule and the contacts especially during an emergency. The daily meeting shallbegin with discussing the safety score and the results of the safety inspection carried out by the second officer on the previous day.The corrective actions to be taken, permits to be issued for the day, all planned work shall also be discussed.3) Yard to be kept informed of all additions and deletions to the specifications as soon as possible and get them to concur on these atevery production / safety meeting.4) Daily count of empty paint drums must be checked by the superintendent and he shall obtain final paint report.5) During the dry dock / repair, the Superintendent to communicate daily with Head Office by E-mail / Fax as well as with Owners ifrequired. The communication should encompass following:· Safety score for the day· Work done by yard· Work done by crew· Survey carried out· Problems encountered during the day· Progress of Damage repairs, if any· Additional jobs, if any· Extra costs, if any anticipated and reasons· Update of expected completion date and costs· Stores and spares received or required6) Superintendent to maintain a log of labour and work done/ times. Delegate as necessary. He is also to maintain records of alldelays, wrong execution of works, labour shortages, maintain separate documentations for H&M and P&I claim work done/ costs.Maintain progressive records through photographs of all important jobs.7) All repairs to be carried out in compliance with Class regulations.8) Just before complete flooding of dry-dock the dry-dock checklist (Form Q 19) to be filled for the dry-docking items in column“AFTER”.9) Prior flooding checks: All bottom plugs removed from WBT have been fitted back. All work with regards to ship sides below thewater line is completed. Sea chest grids fitted and all covers on anodes / sensors removed. When dock is being filled up or floatingdock is lowered all valves and pipelines are free of leaks.6.5.3AFTER DOCKING / REPAIRS1) The work done certificate to be checked carefully before being endorsed by ship staff, with all discrepancies highlighted andremarked upon.2) The bill negotiations with the yard should be carried out and approval to be sought from General Manager / Managing Directorbefore settlement. If unable to reach settlement, draft a written document for items of difference prior return stating clearly stances ofboth sides.3) Once a final agreement of the yard / repair bill and payment terms is reached with the shipyard follow up for funds and effectpayment as per schedule.4) An evaluation of the dry dock / repair yard has to be done after completion of the job including a brief report with lessons learnt andimportant points to take care in next dry dock.5) All matters related to dry-docking / repairs are to be filed in the relevant file.6.5.4RELATED FORMS1) TA 03 Contractor HSE Questionnaire – To be filled prior taking quotations.2) TA 07 Contractor Risk Assessment – To be filled by attending superintendent after completion of dry docking.3) TA 08 Safety Plan – Agreed upon and signed by the Technical Superintendent, Master and Ship Repair Manager beforecommencing work in the yard.4) Q 16 Specification of Repairs – to be use for preparing the repair specifications.5) Q 17 Dry Dock Preamble – to be used for obtaining the quotations.6) Q 18 Dry Dock Safety Inspection – Filled by 2/O (Safety Officer in dry dock) on a daily basis.7) Q 19 Dry Dock Checklist – To be filled before (in order to assess operation of machinery and identify possible defects which maybe dealt with in the dry dock) and after (to confirm all systems are in order) the dry dock by vessel.8) Q 20 Daily Dry Dock Safety Meeting6.6SHIPS DRAWINGS AND PLANSThe Technical Superintendent in charge of the vessel shall be responsible to ensure that all available drawings, instruction books forthe vessels under his charge are available for reference as and when required.
